:"1270–Deceased","after 1 December 1347":"after 1 December 1347","about 1290":"about 1290","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1347":"1347","1324":"1324","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1320":"1320","11 November 1347":"11 November 1347","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1328":"1328","Wortley, Yorkshire, England":"Wortley, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Monk Bretton Priory Lund Wood, Yorkshire, England":"Lund Wood, Yorkshire, England","Lund Wood, Yorkshire, England":"Lund Wood, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Wortley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Wortley in Tankersley (Yorkshire), or Lower, Upper, or New Wortley in Armley (Yorkshire), or (least likely) Wortley in Wotton under Edge (Gloucestershire). The place in Tankersley derives from Old English <i>wyrt</i> ‘plant, vegetable’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The place in Armley derives from an Old English personal name <i>Wyrca</i> or <i>Weorca</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i>. The Gloucestershire placename derives from Old English <i>wyrt</i> + <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Worley","meanings":["English:","habitational name with different origins. In the West Midlands this surname is most probably derived from Great or Little Wyrley in Norton Canes (Staffordshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>wīr</i> ‘bog myrtle’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. In the East Midlands, the name is possibly from Worlick in Ramsey (Huntingdonshire), the etymology of the which is uncertain. In northern England, possibly from Whirley in Over Alderley (Cheshire), which has the same etymology as the Staffordshire names. There may also be a further unlocated source of this habitational name in southern England.","possibly an irregular variant of   Wortley   or   Warley  ."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":0,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":25,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":38,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":47,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicholas De Wortley was born about 1290, in Wortley, Yorkshire, England, his father, Nicholas De Wortley, was 15 and his mother, Sibilla, was 21. He married Lucy De Greystoke in 1317, in Wortley, Yorkshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died on 11 November 1347, in Lund Wood, Yorkshire, England, at the age of 58, and was buried in Lund Wood, Yorkshire, England."},"et":{"about 1290–11 November 1347":"umbes 1290–11. november 1347","1290–1347":"1290–1347","1280–Female":"1280–Surnud","–1347":"–1347","1318–1360":"1318–1360","1320–Male":"1320–Surnud","1322–Male":"1322–Surnud","1324–Male":"1324–Surnud","1277–Male":"1277–Surnud","1270–Female":"1270–Surnud","after 1 December 1347":"pärast 1. detsembrit 1347","about 1290":"umbes 1290","1360":"1360","1270":"1270","1280":"1280","1290":"1290","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1347":"1347","1324":"1324","1322":"1322","1453":"1453","1277":"1277","1320